# bosonic-gates

**Tutorial notebooks and library for bosonic quantum computing with superconducting circuits.**

[![Binder](https://mybinder.org/badge_logo.svg)](https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/YOUR_USERNAME/bosonic-gates/HEAD)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](LICENSE)

---

Bosonic quantum computing encodes quantum information in the Hilbert space of a harmonic oscillator (a microwave cavity). This repository teaches the physics, simulation tools, and control strategies for two key superconducting circuit platforms — the **transmon-cavity system** and the **SNAIL resonator** — from first principles through to optimal control and error budgets.

The presentation style follows [topocm_content](https://github.com/topocm/topocm_content): each module is a self-contained Jupyter notebook with LaTeX theory cells, executable simulation code, interactive widgets, and a companion PDF.

---

## Modules

| Module | Topic | Notebooks |
|--------|-------|-----------|
| **0** | Quantum Harmonic Oscillator Foundations | QHO & ladder operators · Phase space (Wigner, Q-function) · Open systems & Lindblad |
| **1** | Superconducting Circuit Hamiltonians | LC → Josephson junction · Transmon Hamiltonian · Dispersive coupling |
| **2** | SNAIL Nonlinear Oscillator | SNAIL potential & Taylor expansion · Circuit parameters · Driven beam-splitter derivation |
| **3** | Quantum Dynamics | RWA from scratch · Lindblad vs Bloch-Redfield · Floquet-Markov for driven systems |
| **4** | Bosonic Gates | SNAP gates · ECD gates · Gate benchmarking & process tomography |
| **5** | Optimal Control | Propagators & fidelity · GRAPE via JAX autodiff · GRAPE vs Krotov vs CRAB |
| **6** | Error Budget | Error channels · Per-channel infidelity budget · Validity map of master equation methods |

---

## Quick Start

### Browser (no installation)

Click the Binder badge above. All notebooks run in your browser — no local setup required.

> **Note:** Floquet-Markov (module 3) and GRAPE (module 5) notebooks set `N=6, n_steps=64` automatically in Binder mode to stay within memory limits.

### Local Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/bosonic-gates.git
cd bosonic-gates

# Using conda (recommended)
conda env create -f environment.yml
conda activate bosonic-gates
pip install -e ".[dev]"

# Or using pip only
pip install -e ".[dev]"

# Launch Jupyter
jupyter lab
```

### For Developers

```bash
# Run the test suite
pytest tests/

# Smoke-test all notebooks
pytest --nbmake content/ --nbmake-timeout=600

# Build all companion PDFs
bash scripts/build_all_pdfs.sh
```

---

## Prerequisites

This material is aimed at **graduate students and researchers** in quantum engineering who are familiar with:
- Quantum mechanics at the graduate level (Dirac notation, density matrices, open systems)
- Basic circuit QED concepts (oscillators, qubits, dispersive coupling)

No prior knowledge of QuTiP or superconducting circuit simulation is assumed.

---

## Dependencies

| Library | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| [`qutip`](https://qutip.org/) ≥ 5.0 | Quantum dynamics (`mesolve`, `brmesolve`, Floquet) |
| [`qutip-jax`](https://github.com/qutip/qutip-jax) | JAX backend for autodiff GRAPE |
| [`jax`](https://github.com/google/jax) + [`optax`](https://optax.readthedocs.io/) | Autodiff & gradient optimization |
| `numpy`, `scipy` | Numerics |
| `matplotlib`, `ipympl` | Visualization and interactive plots |
| `ipywidgets` | Interactive parameter sliders |
| `sympy` | Symbolic RWA derivation (module 3) |

